00:10:25.706 --> 00:10:28.256
So, what did this mean in practice?

00:10:28.666 --> 00:10:34.936
It meant the build up of the group Al Qaeda, the group that had grown out of the Soviet-Afghan war.

00:10:36.086 --> 00:10:42.286
From 1992 to 1996, Osama bin Laden and Al Qaeda were based

00:10:42.286 --> 00:10:46.126
in Sudan, after the Islamist coup d’état in the country.

00:10:47.484 --> 00:10:51.466
He had been forced to leave Saudi Arabia after criticising the regime,

00:10:51.606 --> 00:10:56.692
and his Saudi passport and citizenship were taken away in 1994.

00:10:58.021 --> 00:11:02.740
Although one could perhaps trace his path to global terrorism back to when

00:11:02.740 --> 00:11:08.408
he was a much younger man, it was in the 1990s, when he was in his mid 30s,

00:11:08.408 --> 00:11:14.238
when he made the transition from regional nuisance to global terrorist threat.

00:11:15.618 --> 00:11:21.898
Al Qaeda, the terrorist group he was head of, continued to grow, and with it, the attacks.

00:11:22.918 --> 00:11:25.978
The first attack that he is believed to have been involved

00:11:25.978 --> 00:11:30.341
with came in 1992, in  Aden, the capital of Yemen.

00:11:31.091 --> 00:11:37.731
But it wouldn’t be until 1998, with the twin bombings of the US embassies in Dar es Salaam

00:11:37.841 --> 00:11:45.871
and Nairobi, that his face became known the world over, and in June of 1999 the FBI would

00:11:45.881 --> 00:11:52.381
decide that he was such a threat that his name would be put on its list of Ten Most Wanted.

00:11:53.681 --> 00:11:57.671
As you might imagine, he was never removed from this list alive.

00:11:58.581 --> 00:12:00.251
So, back to our story.

00:12:00.631 --> 00:12:05.651
Osama bin Laden is now one of the world’s most wanted men, and has had to move

00:12:05.701 --> 00:12:11.131
out of Sudan, now to Afghanistan, the one country that will actually take him.

00:12:12.371 --> 00:12:17.591
He is head of a terrorist group that has carried out attacks across Africa and the Middle East.

00:12:18.311 --> 00:12:23.491
We know this for sure, but what was not clear to everyone was “why”.

00:12:25.021 --> 00:12:30.141
The simplistic answer that was plastered all over American cable TV was that

00:12:30.151 --> 00:12:34.761
he hated American freedoms, but it was slightly more complicated than that.

00:12:36.151 --> 00:12:42.511
The rare pieces of evidence that we have of Osama bin Laden suggest a man fixated

00:12:42.711 --> 00:12:48.841
on one thing, one goal: removing the Western military presence from the Middle East.

00:12:49.881 --> 00:12:53.641
He even said this in an interview with CNN, perhaps the

00:12:53.811 --> 00:12:58.007
most famous American news network, which took place in 1997.

00:12:59.124 --> 00:13:04.201
Perhaps ominously, when asked “what are your future plans”, he responded

00:13:04.671 --> 00:13:07.861
“you’ll see them and hear about them in the media, god willing”.

00:13:09.091 --> 00:13:16.351
Four years later, on September 11th of 2001, the world saw the culmination of his plan, as

00:13:16.391 --> 00:13:21.971
two planes struck the World Trade Center in New York, and another crashed into the Pentagon.

00:13:22.905 --> 00:13:28.031
2,977 people in total were killed, making Osama bin

00:13:28.031 --> 00:13:31.711
Laden responsible for the deadliest attack on US soil.

00:13:33.171 --> 00:13:38.951
The objective, let’s remember, was to push the United States out of the Middle East,

00:13:38.991 --> 00:13:43.761
to frighten the United States government into removing its troops from Saudi Arabia.

00:13:45.371 --> 00:13:50.451
Osama bin Laden thought there would be widespread opposition to entering a

00:13:50.451 --> 00:13:55.181
foreign conflict, and he remembered the public opposition to the war in Vietnam.

00:13:56.351 --> 00:14:00.311
Although Osama bin Laden was clearly an intelligent man

00:14:00.321 --> 00:14:04.901
in many ways, this was a huge miscalculation on his part.

00:14:05.971 --> 00:14:12.714
Not only did the 9/11 attacks result in the US-led invasion of Afghanistan and subsequent

00:14:12.944 --> 00:14:17.364
20-year occupation of the country, which had strong domestic support initially,

00:14:17.364 --> 00:14:22.504
let's remember, but they also made him the highest profile criminal in the world.

00:14:23.614 --> 00:14:29.964
There was a $25 million bounty placed on his head, a reward for his capture,

00:14:30.294 --> 00:14:35.354
and soon it became incredibly hard for him to control his group’s activities.

00:14:36.504 --> 00:14:42.264
For obvious reasons, it’s hard to know exactly what he was doing and where he was in the

00:14:42.264 --> 00:14:47.584
period immediately after the 9/11 attacks - we are talking about the world’s most wanted man

00:14:47.584 --> 00:14:53.404
here - but American intelligence services believe that he spent most of the following years

00:14:53.664 --> 00:14:59.764
moving from safehouse to safehouse in the border region between Afghanistan and Pakistan.

00:15:01.224 --> 00:15:06.920
Now, you probably know how this story ends, or rather, how the life of Osama Bin Laden ends.

00:15:07.970 --> 00:15:16.470
The United States did manage to track him down, to find him, and on May 2nd of 2011, just

00:15:16.470 --> 00:15:22.210
after one o’ clock in the morning, a helicopter with an elite team of US forces descended

00:15:22.360 --> 00:15:29.140
on a compound in Abbottabad, in Pakistan, where they found, shot and killed Osama bin Laden.

00:15:30.460 --> 00:15:34.510
This much you probably know already, but what is more interesting

00:15:34.510 --> 00:15:39.420
to dwell on, to talk about, is what was discovered during the raid.

00:15:41.000 --> 00:15:46.330
In the compound where bin Laden was hiding, the US forces discovered a treasure trove

00:15:46.330 --> 00:15:53.660
of information, hard drives containing 470,000 different files that give us some

00:15:53.710 --> 00:15:59.880
indication of what bin Laden had been doing, and help us to understand bin Laden the man.

00:16:01.180 --> 00:16:03.140
So, what do they tell us?

00:16:04.010 --> 00:16:09.660
Firstly, and perhaps unsurprisingly, given how wanted he was, he was

00:16:09.680 --> 00:16:14.860
incredibly cut off from Al Qaeda, the group he was nominally in charge of.

00:16:15.650 --> 00:16:21.690
He had no internet or telephone line, and was only able to communicate with people via letters.

00:16:22.510 --> 00:16:27.091
And clearly, if you’re trying to run what is essentially a multinational

00:16:27.241 --> 00:16:31.481
21st century business, this makes communication very difficult.

00:16:33.021 --> 00:16:37.111
Secondly, and despite how difficult it was to communicate

00:16:37.111 --> 00:16:41.302
with the outside world, he was a serious micromanager.

00:16:41.601 --> 00:16:45.491
He obsessed over details, and would leave nothing up to chance.

00:16:45.981 --> 00:16:52.551
He would send letters to trusted associates, but these would be handwritten, then scanned and

00:16:52.551 --> 00:16:58.641
put onto an encrypted flash drive and taken, physically, to whoever needed to receive them.

00:17:00.041 --> 00:17:05.275
Thirdly, and this is in stark contrast to many portrayals of

00:17:05.275 --> 00:17:09.735
him, he did seem to put great trust in his wives and daughters.

00:17:10.515 --> 00:17:13.805
He is thought to have married five times, and at the

00:17:13.815 --> 00:17:17.345
time of his death he was found with three of his wives.

00:17:18.605 --> 00:17:26.465
These three were all highly intelligent women, all with PhDs, doctorate qualifications, and the

00:17:26.485 --> 00:17:33.197
files found at his house show that he turned to them for advice on a wide variety of matters.

00:17:33.574 --> 00:17:36.135
And it was a similar case with his daughters.

00:17:37.105 --> 00:17:41.725
The fourth thing, which is related to the third point actually, because it was

00:17:41.725 --> 00:17:46.675
a frequent topic of conversation between him and his wives, is how troubled he

00:17:46.675 --> 00:17:52.810
was by the Arab Spring, the revolutions in the Arab world that started in 2010.

00:17:53.760 --> 00:17:56.500
Now, why was he disturbed by this, you might ask?

00:17:56.870 --> 00:18:00.710
You might have thought that it presented an opportunity, as

00:18:00.900 --> 00:18:04.690
corrupt rulers were being toppled, were being overturned.

00:18:05.510 --> 00:18:09.240
Indeed, bin Laden did write that the chaos could present

00:18:09.250 --> 00:18:13.340
an opportunity for Al Qaeda thoughts and ideas to spread.

00:18:14.460 --> 00:18:21.260
But, more importantly, it seemed that he wasn’t sure where the Arab Spring left Al Qaeda.

00:18:22.150 --> 00:18:28.710
If Western-backed regimes could be toppled peacefully, or at least relatively peacefully

00:18:28.870 --> 00:18:34.700
compared to bombings and the deaths of Muslim civilians, then what was the role of Al Qaeda?

00:18:35.220 --> 00:18:36.660
Where did it fit in?

00:18:37.800 --> 00:18:42.490
He was also concerned that instability in the region would mean that US forces

00:18:42.510 --> 00:18:47.090
would move in, which was exactly the thing that he had always fought against.

00:18:48.560 --> 00:18:50.920
Clearly, he had reason to be fearful.

00:18:51.860 --> 00:18:59.680
The United States has left Afghanistan, but there are still reported to be between 45,000 and 65,000

00:18:59.710 --> 00:19:05.590
American troops in the Middle East, split between Saudi Arabia and other Persian Gulf nations.

00:19:06.500 --> 00:19:10.370
Of course, it’s perfectly acceptable to debate whether these troops

00:19:10.550 --> 00:19:15.030
should be there, but the reality is that bin Laden thought that attacking

00:19:15.030 --> 00:19:19.640
the US would get them out, and in fact it did exactly the opposite.

00:19:20.940 --> 00:19:24.820
And his legacy is, well, it’s complicated of course.

00:19:25.500 --> 00:19:30.630
On the one hand Al Qaeda is thankfully now significantly weakened, although

00:19:30.820 --> 00:19:35.380
there are some commentators who suggest a newly Taliban-controlled Afghanistan

00:19:35.610 --> 00:19:39.640
will give it more breathing room, and allow it to build up strength.

00:19:40.950 --> 00:19:47.130
On the other hand, he became the poster boy for Islamic terrorism, a hero

00:19:47.170 --> 00:19:51.700
and icon, someone whose name attacks could be carried out on behalf of.

00:19:53.820 --> 00:19:59.800
When he was killed, although his body was quickly disposed of at sea, he became a martyr

00:19:59.830 --> 00:20:06.100
for jihadists, someone who gave up his huge family riches and wealth in his “holy quest”.

00:20:07.450 --> 00:20:11.670
Let's be clear though, he was a violent terrorist, someone who was not

00:20:11.710 --> 00:20:16.890
afraid of killing men, women and children, muslims and non-muslims alike.

00:20:17.360 --> 00:20:21.970
There is no excusing or denying that, and one must underline that he

00:20:21.970 --> 00:20:26.060
was directly responsible for the deaths of thousands of people, and

00:20:26.250 --> 00:20:30.620
indirectly perhaps responsible for hundreds or thousands times more.

00:20:31.650 --> 00:20:37.820
But to portray him as merely a simple cave-dwelling Western-hating terrorist is

00:20:37.820 --> 00:20:43.050
to somewhat miss the point, and to only scrape the surface of the complicated

00:20:43.070 --> 00:20:48.000
ideology and legacy of Osama bin Laden, the world’s most wanted man.

